hut down the Chicago school system for seven days.A Fight for the Soul of Public Education takes into account two overlapping, parallel, and equally important stories. One is a grassroots story of worker activism told from the perspective of rank-and-file union members and their community supporters. Ashby and Bruno provide a detailed account of how the strike became an international cause when other teachers unions had largely surrendered to corporate-driven education reform. The second story describes the role of state and national politics in imposing educational governance changes on public schools and draconian limitations on union bargaining rights. It includes a detailed account of the actual bargaining process revealing the mundane and the transcendental strategies of both school board and union representatives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEducation and statezIllinoiszChicago. 0aStrikes and lockoutsxTeacherszIllinoiszChicago. 0aTeachersxPolitical activityzIllinoiszChicago. 4aEducation & History Of Education. 4aLabor History. 4aU.S. History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh  aPublic education, labor relations, school systems, educational governance, school board, union representatives.1 aBruno, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170593940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501705939423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501705939/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL